{
  "text": "Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (NPC) is a malignancy most strongly associated with the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and radiotherapy is the most effective treatment against NPC. However, due to radioresistance, locoregional recurrence or metastatic spread still occurs in a high proportion of patients who undergo radiotherapy [CITATION_1] . Latent membrane protein 1 (LMP1) is an EBVencoded protein with oncogenic properties [CITATION_2] . LMP1 plays an essential role in tumorigenesis of NPCs through the activity of various signal pathways and is thus a potential target for NPC biotherapy [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Downregulation of LMP1 was shown to be potentially effective in the prevention of NPC metastasis and reduction of NPC radioresistance [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . However, the mechanism of LMP1-mediated radioresistance is not entirely clear.",
  "correct_citation": {
